@Node DoorNotes "Door Notes"

  Door Notes
  ==========

    USER doors with names that end with a '!' character can not
    be started by the user from the command prompt.  This is so that
    you can create doors that are not system doors that you wouldn't
    normally want a user to be able to run but that you would want
    them to run from other parts of the bbs, like a special screen.

    You can still define a new system door name, and call that from
    a screen file.

    So to re-cap, you can do either this:

    Commands/System

    MySysDoor_Type_1=HBBS
    MySysDoor_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/System/MySysDoor/MySysDoor.HBBS

    then in a screen file:

    @^SYSDOOR^MySysDoor myoptions@

    OR:

    Commands/Level_#?

    MyUserDoor!_Type_1=HBBS
    MyUserDoor!_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/User/MyUserDoor/MyUserDoor.HBBS

    then in a screen file:

    @^USERDOOR^MyUserDoor! myoptions@

    But, in both examples, the user wouldn't be able to type in
    either "MySysDoor" or "MyUserDoor!" at the command prompt.

    There are no *real* differences between a system door and a user
    door, in terms of coding.  But using the correct location for
    a door is useful.

    It's easier to define a door in a Commands/Level_#? file
    then a Commands/System file if you want  different doors for
    different access levels.  (as system doors are run by the
    system for ALL users, regardless of access level, but the
    user's access level is checked before a user door can even be
    started)

    You can still check the user's access level from a door and then
    do different things depending on it though...

@EndNode
